The North Berkeley Farmers’ Market was surprisingly bustling on Thursday afternoon, with farmers hawking petite cone cabbages, oyster mushrooms and golden beets.
Some, like the Downtown Palo Alto Farmers’ Market, decided to shut down on their own.
“Many people depend on farmers’ markets for their food and many farmers depend on farmers’ markets for their livelihood.”Farmers’ markets are known in the Bay Area as not just a place to shop but to socialize, eat and enjoy the outdoors.
“It will greatly impact people who are the most vulnerable if farmers’ markets don’t remain open,” she said.
As part of the California Alliance of Farmers’ Markets, Brinkman is fighting to get some closed markets reopened.